	(text "This is a project for practicing PCB design and programming.\n\nThe result is a device that is powered either with a battery or with a USB connection.\nThe device can recharge the battery via the USB connection.\n\nThe device includes:\n  - An example sensor (temperature)\n  - External flash for updating the firmware over the air (FOTA)\n  - A modem module that connects the main microcontroller to the internet with LTE CAT-M1\n  - Option to use either an external antenna or an integrated antenna\n\nA key goal of the project is to ensure it has as little reliance as possible on totalitarian\ncountries (e.g., China or Russia) or on hostile countries (e.g., USA).\nComponent sourcing must be done carefully to select manufacturers who can supply parts\nthat are not produced in such countries.\nInstead, democratic countries (e.g., Taiwan and Germany) should be preferred.\n\nTo reduce strain on the global environment, manufacturing and sourcing is centered around\nEurope.\n\nFor manufacturing, the following companies are recommended:\n- Aisler (Germany)\n- Aspocomp? (Finland)\n\nFor components, the following companies are recommended:\n- Würth Elektronik (Germany)\n- Infineon Technologies (Germany)\n- STMicroelectronics (Italy)\n\nFor suppliers, the following companies are recommended:\n- Transfer Multisort Elektronik (Poland)\n- RS Components (England)"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 15.24 63.5 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 2.54 2.54)
				(thickness 0.3175)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "b94eda75-5ba9-4359-bbae-047503216cba")
	)
	(text "Place a stitched GND guard rail around the edges of the PCB\nto provide a grounding point for human touch when handling the device."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 330.2 228.6 0)
		(effects
